ull,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe surgeon is holding up a loop of jejunum and a number of diverticula are visible along the mesenteric border. Small bowel diverticula are much less common than their colonic counterparts and usually occur along the mesenteric border, at sites where mesenteric blood vessels enter the wall of the small intestine. They tend to occur in older patients and are found in perhaps 0.5% of this population. Their aetiology is unknown. They are usually \u003Cstrong\u003Eincidental findings\u003C/strong\u003E during an imaging investigation or surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOccasionally they can become symptomatic and ulceration within the diverticulum could cause bleeding (\u003Cstrong\u003Eanaemia\u003C/strong\u003E), inflammation or perforation. It is also thought that stasis within the diverticula could lead to bacterial overgrowth, with symptoms of \u003Cstrong\u003Emalabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eflatulence\u003C/strong\u003E. If one of these diverticula did become inflamed - which is very unlikely - it could lead to an episode of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintestinal obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Small bowel diverticula are usually asymptomatic."],"references":["Makris K, Tsiotos GG, Stafyla V, et al. Small Intestinal Nonmeckelian Diverticulosis. J Clin Gastroenterol. 2009;43:201-07. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19142169/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28455"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1369"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15317"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15317"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7370ce0f-0e0e-4c0c-ae8d-eeb5e5c57292.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7370ce0f-0e0e-4c0c-ae8d-eeb5e5c57292.jpg","isPr